    "content": "nullReport and Reduce Your Carbon Footprint with Net Zero Cloud\nTABLE OF CONTENTS\nClose\nClose\nSearch\nSearch\n Report and Reduce Your Carbon Footprint with Net Zero Cloud\n Get Ready to Use Net Zero Cloud\n Determine the Sources to Inventory\n Emissions Factors That Affect Calculations\n Create Your Consumption Records\n Manage Scope 3 Value Chain Data\n Manage Your Carbon Footprint\n Manage Your Water Footprint\n Manage the Annual Emissions Inventory\n Record Locking and Recalculation\n Benchmark Building Energy Intensity Data\n Manage Carbon Footprint Data Gaps\n Set Emissions Targets\n Emissions Forecasting\n Carbon Accounting for Extended Organizational Boundaries\n Carbon Accounting for Partner Community Users\n Engage Suppliers for Emissions Reduction\n Create a Supplier Scorecard\n Gather Supplier’s Sustainability Scorecard Information\n Associate Procurement Items with Supplier Data\n Allocate Supplier Data to Procurement Items\n Calculate Emissions Based On Quantity or Spending\n Create a Supplier Product Record\n Sharing Data With Suppliers\n Example: Calculate Quantity-Based Emissions\n Allocate Carbon Credits to Offset Unavoidable Emissions\n Allocate Energy Attribute Certificate Credits to Reduce Scope 2...\n Report Social and Governance Data with Net Zero Cloud\n Generate Disclosures by Using Disclosure and Compliance Hub\n Data Collection\n Improve Decarbonization Strategy with Sustainability Programs\n Data Auditing\n Submit Records for Approval\n Use Net Zero Analytics App\n Use DEI Analytics App\n Report Your Carbon Footprint\n\nYou are here:\n\nSALESFORCE HELP\nDOCS\nREPORT AND REDUCE YOUR CARBON FOOTPRINT WITH NET ZERO CLOUD\nCalculate Emissions Based On Quantity or Spending\n\nCollect and capture product-level emissions factors from suppliers and general industries resources to calculate emissions for Scope 3, Category 1: Purchased Goods and Services based on quantity or spending. Calculating emissions based on quantity improves the accuracy and granularity of the Scope 3 accounting and also provides data for more sustainable sourcing choices.\n\nREQUIRED EDITIONS\nAvailable in: Lightning Experience\nAvailable in: Enterprise, Performance, Unlimited, and Developer Editions\n\nWhen you use the spend-based method to calculate emissions for goods and services, you collect data on the economic value of goods and services purchased and multiply it by the relevant industry average Environmentally-Extended Input-Output (EEIO) emission factors. By using the spend-based method, the emissions calculation considers how much you’ve spent for procurement irrespective of the relative carbon intensity of the supplier from whom the goods and services were procured. For example, a supplier can implement a lower carbon but more costly manufacturing process than their peers, and raise prices accordingly. If the spend-based method is used for calculation, the emissions will be relatively and inaccurately high compared to their peers. Using a supplier-specific product emissions factor will provide more accurate results.\n\nWhen you use the quantity-based method to calculate emissions for goods and services, you use an emissions factor for each product unit purchased. For example, instead of calculating steel per dollar spent, you can calculate the quantity of steel purchased multiplied by a specific steel emissions factor. You can collect these factors from suppliers or use known generic industry-wide emissions factors. By using the quantity-based method, the emissions calculation considers the supplier’s per-unit emissions for the goods and services procured. For example, a supplier can implement a lower carbon but more costly manufacturing process than their peers, and raise prices accordingly. If the quantity-based method is used for calculation, the emissions will be low compared to their peers. The supplier is potentially more sustainable because of the low emissions per unit quantity that is procured.\n\nCreate a Supplier Product Record\nCreate a record to track supplier-specific data about a product that is purchased from that supplier.\nSharing Data With Suppliers\nShare supplier product data and product emissions factor data with suppliers in an Experience Cloud site by using sharing sets and a sharing rule category.\nExample: Calculate Quantity-Based Emissions\nConsider calculating emissions based on supplier quantities.\nDID THIS ARTICLE SOLVE YOUR ISSUE?\nLet us know so we can improve!\nYes\nNo\n ",
